President Trump delivered remarks at the National Archives Museum in Washington, D.C. during the White House Conference on American History. He emphasized the importance of defending America's founding principles and teaching the truth about the country's history to future generations. The President criticized the radical movement that seeks to demolish America's heritage, including tearing down statues and spreading violence and anarchy. He denounced the left-wing indoctrination in schools and the propagation of critical race theory, stating that it is harmful to children and the unity of the nation. President Trump announced the establishment of the "1776 Commission," a national commission to promote patriotic education, and the creation of the National Garden of American Heroes, a park featuring statues of great Americans. He also mentioned the addition of a statue of Caesar Rodney, a signer of the Declaration of Independence, to the National Garden.